§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ We integrate over a product space by integrating one
    coordinate at a time. ⦉
⦉

§ Result ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ Let $(X, 𝒜, μ)$ and $(Y, 𝒜, ν)$ be $σ$-finite measurable
    spaces. ⦉

  ‖ Let $f: X × Y → \eri$ be $𝒜 × ℬ$-measurable and $μ ×
    ν$-integrable. ⦉

  ‖ Then
    𝍫 ⦊
      ‣ ‖ For $μ$-almost every $x$ in $X$ the section $f_x$ is
          $ν$-integrable and for $ν$-almost every $y$ in $Y$ the section
          $f^y$ is $μ$-integrable, ⦉⦉

      ‣ ‖ the functions $I_f$ and $J_f$ defined by
          ◇ ⦊
            ‖ I_f(x) = \begin{cases} ⦉

            ‖ ∫_{Y} f_x dν ＆\text{ if } ⦉

            ‖ f_x \text{ is } ν\text{-integrable}, ᜶ ⦉

            ‖ 0 ＆ \text{ otherwise} ⦉

            ‖ \end{cases} ⦉
          ⦉
          and
          ◇ ⦊
            ‖ J_f(y) = \begin{cases} ⦉

            ‖ ∫_{X} f^y dμ ＆\text{ if } f^y \text{ is }
              μ\text{-integrable}, ᜶ ⦉

            ‖ 0 ＆ \text{ otherwise} ⦉

            ‖ \end{cases} ⦉
          ⦉
          belong to $ℒ(X, 𝒜, μ, 𝗥)$ and $ℒ(Y, 𝒜, ν, 𝗥)$ respectively,
          and ⦉

        ‣ ‖ the relation
            ◇ ⦊
              ‖ ∫_{X × Y} f d(μ × ν) = ∫_{X} I_f dμ = ∫_{Y}
                J_f dν ⦉
            ⦉
            holds. ⦉⦉⦉
    ⦉⦉
</statement>
¶ ⦊
  ‖ The above is called ❬Fubini's Theorem❭. ⦉

  ‖ Next: ❬Tonelli's theorem❭. ⦉
⦉
